    <fr:title text="Sup norm">Sup norm</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
    <fr:date>
      <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
      <fr:month>5</fr:month>
      <fr:day>26</fr:day>
    </fr:date>
    <fr:authors>
      <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
    </fr:authors>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>The sup norm (or supremum norm, or uniform norm, or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^\infty ]]></fr:tex> norm) of a bounded function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f: X \rightarrow  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> (or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>) is defined as:</fr:p>
    <fr:p>
      <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||f||_\infty  = \sup _{x \in  X} |f(x)|]]></fr:tex>
    </fr:p>
    <fr:p>where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sup ]]></fr:tex> denotes the supremum, or least upper bound, of the set of values.</fr:p>
    <fr:p>For the space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C(X)]]></fr:tex> of continuous functions on a compact set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, the sup norm makes <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C(X)]]></fr:tex> into a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000F.xml" addr="FA-000F" title="Banach Space">Banach space</fr:link>.</fr:p>
    <fr:p>The sup norm measures the maximum absolute value that a function attains on its domain.</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
